  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Be it known unto the king,.... The intent of this letter was, that it might be known to the king what follows: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "that the Jews which came up from thee to us are come unto Jerusalem; this they observe partly out of contempt of the Jews, having been lately captive in Babylon, and partly to insinuate what ingratitude they were guilty of; that having got their liberty, and come to Jerusalem, they made use of it to the king's detriment: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "building the rebellious and the bad city; as they suggest it had been to kings, even his predecessors, in former times, Ezra 4:15 ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "building the rebellious and the bad city; as they suggest it had been to kings, even his predecessors, in former times, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Ezra 4:15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and have set up the walls thereof, and joined the foundations; which was a falsehood; for the most they had done was setting up the walls of their houses in Jerusalem, and laying the foundation of the temple; as for the walls of the city, they had not as yet done anything unto them. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "and have set up the walls thereof, and joined the foundations; which was a falsehood; for the most they had done was setting up the walls of their houses in Jerusalem, and laying the foundation of the temple; as for the walls of the city, they had not as yet done anything unto them. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
